        <h1>a race to clean water</h1>
        <p>the story behind flint michigan</p>
        <p>Caroline Plante <br>jnl221</p>
        <p>Posted on 04/17/2002, at 9:00 p.m.</p>
      </header>

      <img src="https://www.americanrivers.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/flint-river-michigan-1440x675.jpg" alt="storyimage">
      <p class="caption">©American Rivers, 2016</p>

      <p>The Flint Michigan Water Crisis began in April 2014. To this day, there is still lead found in their water. The EPA has a series of <a href="https://www.epa.gov/flint/flint-drinking-water-faqs"> recommendations</a> so households can access safe drinking water. Eight years later, drinkable water without household filtration systems is not yet a reality for residents of Flint.
</p>
      <p>The initial crisis sparked discussions country wide of the city’s lead levels. However, years later Flint’s water is barely drinkable without a household filtration system. This water crisis has lasting effects to this day for the residents of Flint, Michigan and surrounding towns. 
</p>

      <p>Linden, Michigan resident Grant Maxheimer experienced the height of the Flint Water Crisis when he was just 12 years old. He grew up near Flint, just far enough to be on the outside looking in. Maxheimer was in public school just 15 minutes outside of Flint. Although his school was not directly affected, he had a front row seat to the crisis at a young age.
</p>

      <p> This sparked a need for change in the adolescent's eyes. Maxheimer knew he wanted to make a difference early into his childhood after watching an area so close to him struggle for a basic human need: water. Seeing an area so close to him without clean water was a pivotal moment in Maxheimer’s life.
  </p>

      <p>Maxheimer, now 19, works with the Syracuse Neighborhood and Business Development Office. His current work focuses on remediating lead paint out of homes with children under six years old who meet certain income guidelines. Although he did not come to Syracuse in search of working in the lead area, the water crisis catalyzed his goals to engage in his community for the betterment of others. He takes his work as an opportunity to shape the new community in which he is a part of.
</p>

      <p>Although just a young teen when the water crisis was at its peak, Maxheimer says he wishes he could’ve done more. His current work is a reflection of that. His youth is a large reason why he works to improve the quality of life in his current community. Maxheimer says the water crisis shaped his future aspirations.
</p>

      <p>“It didn’t affect my life in the sense that we had contaminated water but it was the turning point that I started doing more community engagement work and the first time that deep inequality was ever presented to me”
</p>

      <p>Maxheimer spends his time addressing the lead crisis in Syracuse.
      </p>

