      <p>This graphic displays lead levels in 2017, post water crisis. The data can be found <a href="https://guides.emich.edu/datathon/data">here </a>.</p>

      <p>The chart above shows the average amounts of lead (µg/L) found in the water at different schools. The EPA set a maximum of <a href="https://extension.psu.edu/lead-in-drinking-water#:~:text=Accounting%20for%20other%20sources%20of,water%20at%2015%20%C2%B5g%2FL.">15µg/L.</a> Three years later and five of the eight schools still lack drinkable waterSchools are a key area when looking at the crisis because it extends to people of all ages.
</p>

     <p>Teachers and other staff members cover a multitude of age groups, while the students fill in the rest of the years. The effect the water crisis has on schools affects people of all age ranges across the city. Entire schools had to turn to the reliability of bottled water to get through, and to this day some people are still using them.
</p>

